            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">The Legislature Tried to Act. Both Bills Failed.</h2>

            <p>
              Two bills introduced during the 2025-2026 Washington legislative session attempted to address the copper theft crisis. Neither made it out of committee.
            </p>
            <br>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">House Bill 2213</h3>
            <p>
              Sponsored by Representatives Ryu, Leavitt, Bronoske, Goodman, and Reeves, <a href="https://app.leg.wa.gov/billsummary?BillNumber=2213&Year=2025" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">HB 2213</a> would have required scrap metal recyclers to photograph nonferrous metal and upload images to a database approved by Washington State Patrol. It proposed a 10-day holding period before recyclers could sell scrap, eliminated cash payments in favor of checks or electronic transfers, and created a "critical infrastructure crime reduction unit" to investigate metal theft. The bill failed to advance out of the Committee on Consumer Protection & Business.
            </p>
            <br>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Senate Bill 6190</h3>
            <p>
              Sponsored by Sen. Tina Orwall (D-Des Moines), <a href="https://app.leg.wa.gov/billsummary/?BillNumber=6190&Chamber=Senate&Year=2025" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">SB 6190</a> would have created a new felony for "destruction of critical communications infrastructure" and allowed civil lawsuits against copper thieves to recover damages and legal fees. It also failed to advance. Senator Orwall has indicated she plans to reintroduce the bill next session.
            </p>
            <br>

            <p>
